<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Energy and Climate Change Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Oil &amp; Gas UK (HOT06)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Oil &amp; Gas UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is the principal trade association for the offshore oil and gas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exploration and production </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">industry in the United Kingdom, with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more than 370 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">member companies, comprising oil and gas operators and investors and a broad spectrum of the supply chain: contractors, suppliers, law firms and consultants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> pleasure in submitting our evidence to the Energy and Climate Change Committee’s inquiry </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">into heat.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In the public debate about energy during recent years, there has been a lot of emphasis on electricity, but little about heat (or transport).  In overall terms, only about 35% of the primary energy consumed in the UK is used as electricity; the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> remaining 65% has two main forms of consumption, namely heat, where gas is the principal source, and transport, where oil is dominant.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">While industrial heat demand is reasonably constant, domestic demand is highly seasonal, being almost entirely temperat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ure dependent.  The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">variation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between summer and winter demand is large and, because gas provides 80% of domestic properties (and a large proportion of smaller commercial premises) with heat, the demand for gas varies widely as the seasons change.  However</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, gas is well suited to this; it is much more flexible than electricity which has to be balanced instantaneously, whereas gas does not – it is normally balanced over a 24 hour period.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Terms of Reference</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are others who are better placed than Oil &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas UK to answer the Committee’s 12 questions and so we are taking the opportunity to make some broader points relevant to this inquiry, but also answering the specific question about the relative merits of using gas in space heating.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">General Points Relat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ing to the Inquiry</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The following </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">general </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">points provide </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">some context for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the specific</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> questions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of the Committee’s inquiry:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas is the largest source of primary energy in the country; its main use is for heat, but it also provides a significant share of p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ower generation’s requirements, a share which is likely to increase over the next 15 years or so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">large amounts of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">- and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> oil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-fired</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and nuclear generating capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> retired.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The gas system in the UK delivers far more energy to consumers (of all ty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">pes) than the electricity system does.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  According to National Grid’s latest </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">UK Future Energy Scenarios</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, published in July, annual demand for gas is forecast to decline only slowly and peak demand for gas to remain almost constant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> between now and 2030.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">On</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a day of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">very </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">high demand in cold winter weather, such as has been experienced in several recent winters, if all the heat provided by gas were converted into heat provided by electricity, the peak demand </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> electricity would be multiplied by a factor of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">four, or possibly five.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Again according to National Grid</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, heat supply from gas throughout the economy is forecast to decline only slowly between now and 2030, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heat supply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> become</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> appreciably more electric from about 2035.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Overall demand for heat, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">however, is forecast by National Grid to remain almost constant until 2030, rising slowly thereafter.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The biggest savings in demand for residential heat are coming from the conversion of gas boilers to modern, highly efficient ones, not from the insulation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of properties.  National Grid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">foresees the market in boiler conversions and insulating existing properties becoming saturated by the mid-2020s.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Heat pumps work best in well insulated buildings and, where used in existing buildings, make the most economic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">sense for those properties currently heated by electric, resistive heating and, after those, in properties heated by oil. They </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">will be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">beneficial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in properties heated by gas, especially where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> modern, high efficiency boiler ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> been installed.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Speci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">fic Question Regarding the Use of Gas in Space Heating</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Q.6:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“What are the relative merits of using gas to directly pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">vide space heating compared with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> central electricity production plus domestic heat pumps?”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a number of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> advantages of using gas directly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to provide space heating</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas is a primary source of energy and so</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, in converting gas to heat,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> there are no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ne of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">losses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">associated with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">converting it to a secondary source</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of energy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, such as happens when a primary sour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ce is converted into electricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> before</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the resulting electricity is turned into heat</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The best </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(i.e. super-critical) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">coal fired power stations achieve about 45% thermal efficiency and the best gas fired ones about 58%, so there are s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ignificant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> losses inv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">olved</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in generating electricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  The best coal fired power station in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">this country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, Drax, is not super-critical and only achieves 38% thermal efficiency.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">national </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gas transmission system </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">(NTS) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">probably</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has the necessary </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">overall </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capacity for m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ost </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">future </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">requirements</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but will no doubt require some investment to take account of changing patterns of supply and demand</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The NTS</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> has also proved to be very flexible in its operation during testing conditions in the past five winters.  By contrast, th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e electricity grid is going to need substantial investment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">because its capacity will have to be enlarged in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">a more electrified </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">future.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  This will be expensive.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, as mentioned above, gas does not need to be balanced instantaneously (which electri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">city does) and gas can be stored at scale (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">electricity cannot).  Indeed, the NTS itself acts as a short term store of gas by virtue of “linepack”, i.e. the ability to compress the gas in the system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">during the night</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, when demand is lower,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and use such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> extra gas during the day, as required.  This is impossible with electricity.  A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s a means of delivering energy to users, gas is much more flex</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ible than electricity</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The conversion of gas directly into heat is highly efficient (c. 90%) where modern applianc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">es </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> used.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  This is better than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">modern </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">combined heat and power plants </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">gene</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rally achieve (c. 80%).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">v)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas heati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ng</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> gives households and smaller commercial premises complete control over heat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> building</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  District </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">or similar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heating systems, however good, do not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">generally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide the same degree of local control.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vi)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas heating is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">better </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">than a heat pump</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">thermally inefficient buildings, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">such as are common in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.  The incoming heat is at a lower temperature with a heat pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mp than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is delivered by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a gas boiler</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">eat pumps </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">operate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> best </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">at constant load, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">with well insulated buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and are not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">well </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">suited to poorly insulated ones</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">vii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">etrofitting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">heat pumps to existing properties means that they will mostly be of the ai</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">r source type.  Although ground source heat pumps are more efficient than air source, they are more costly and, obviously, require land adjacent to a building which is not generall</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y available in towns and cities, where the majority of people live.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">viii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In cold </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">weather, air source heat pumps operate at reduced efficiency and require “topping up” by electricity in order to maintain their heating effect which, therefore, places an additional load on electricity supplies at time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> of highest demand.  National Grid fo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">resees electricity demand for heating rising rapidly from 2035 in its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Future Energy Scenarios</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, especially if its “Gone Green” scenario applies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, but less so in the case of “Slow Progression”.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ix)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Gas fired power stations are going to be required </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in considerable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> numbers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> over the next 15-20 years in order to</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.05pt; padding-left:4.95pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">back up intermittent renewable generation;</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.56pt; padding-left:4.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rovide base load generation, given the extent of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">closures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of the existing fleet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">of oil-,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> coal-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and early gas-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">fired</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> nuclear power stations between now and the mid-2020s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – no other technology can do this at the scale required, in the time available and at a cost</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> which is affordable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">But, it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">make no sense to convert gas into electricity at a power station and then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">to convert the electricity generated into heat within buildings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> in order to satisfy demand during cold</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">er</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> weather.  This is inherently less efficient than converting gas directly into heat within buildings.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Therefore, given the nature of the building stoc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">k of this country, the high penetration of gas in supplying space heating and the current programme of conversion to high efficiency boilers, it seems inevitable that gas will continue to have a major role in heating until at least 2030.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We trust that thi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s submission is helpful to the Committee’s inquiry.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  If there are any queries relating to our submission, please do not hesitate to contact us.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt">  See </span><a href="http://www.nationalgrid.com/uk/Gas/OperationalInfo/TBE/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.nationalgrid.com/uk/Gas/OperationalInfo/TBE/</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:9pt"> </span></p></body></html>